Hey! Just a heads up. The `restart_child/1` is not restarting a running process. This tests succeeds because the `Server` is not restarted. To test for a successful restart you can do:

```
assert :ok == Supervisor.restart_child(Todo.Supervisor, Server)
```

love this! 🤩 this module will disappear soon tho as i want to use ocaml 5 custom tracing events for this lower-level stuff, but for the Logger module that'd be more user-friendly (especially a console formatter) i'd love to see more emojis.

Are we really using all of these typefaces/sizes? Could we limit ourselves to a couple of weights and 2 typefaces?

Not sure what the actual impact on load time is but it feels unnecessary to have all of these available.
@brianamarie hi and thanks for the feedback! I presume this is what you meant in your last comment? It doesn't seem to be working 😢
No worries :) I ended up building the clone url with the `user.username` and `repo` globals.
Oh my! I overlooked this. Typically I like keeping it to see the list of changes that actually took place. This can be amended thou
Thanks! Didn't spot that for some reason, I might not be running the linter properly?
I was running `npm run lint-markdown`. I used `npm test` and that works, so I should use that instead. Also my precommit hook doesn't seem to be working? I'll make sure to run `npm test` from now on.
It'd be more idiomatic to use a Gemfile and call `bundle`, and the `lint` rule will be slightly simpler since you'd avoid the path fiddling.

You're right. If we're going the Bundle way, a Rakefile would be a bit more appropriate, but then we have a bunch more dependencies than before.

It'd be easy enough to switch to a Gemfile/Bundle if we see we need more gems down the way. Right now this is more than appropriate. I guess I just got a bit scared at the lint command path fiddling haha, maybe just doing `find pages -exec ./.gem/bin/mdl {}` would make it a bit more clear?

Also remember to add `--no-rdoc --no-ri` as flags to the `gem install` command so it doesn't download the docs for the gem.
Steak sauce!

答案是，你不需要。JSON中的`{}`花括号代表对象，对象中的属性（在语义上）是无序的，也就是说，它的顺序是不可依靠的。JSON中有两种东西：

- `{"a":1,"b":2}` 这是对象，其属性是无序的
- ["a","b"] 这是列表，其元素是有序的
如果用StringBuilder的话，它自带reverse方法的。

Because json properties can be null, json schema classes require many nullable annotations.
And, these annotations do not help reduce NRE.
So I decide to disable annotations.

In many cases, --including MicroBatchFramework.Tests--, `Context` is used without checking if it is `null`.
So annotate that `Context` is non-null.

The new API lets you partially redefine fields on the model itself, and will merge them automatically so in your own module you can just write:

    partner_id = fields.Many2one(required=True)

and it'll just set `required` to `True` on the existing partner_id field. Because selection fields are somewhat more complex there's specific support for them [via a `selection_add` parameter](https://www.odoo.com/documentation/8.0/reference/orm.html#openerp.fields.Selection) which extends the selection's values instead of overwriting the existing ones (as redefining `selection=` would)

> So I must use selection_add parameter instead?

Yes. If you use `selection` it'll overwrite existing choices, if you use `selection_add` it'll add whatever you provide to the existing choices.

> This would more elegantly prepare these idioms for Python 3.

The problem with that is the semantics difference: in Python 3, none of these returns lists (that's Python 2), they all return iterators (map, filter, zip) or iterable "view objects" (range, dict methods).

The other component is that here we can (and should) forbid the builtins entirely during the transition to ensure cross-version compatibility by having a semantically coherent "bridge" via pycompat e.g. not have zip() calls which look good but lead to code actually relying on a `list()` output which will break in P3.

> A lot less efforts overall.

It's way more effort to check each range() callsite to ensure they're not being used as list generators than to just convert them all to a version agnostic "wrapper" and forbid the builtin altogether

>  We can deal with exceptions later if we ever encounter one. We have a testsuite for that.

We don't have a Python 3 runbot which could even remotely run the test suite.

init_column is used to set up a specific column but there's no guarantee other columns of the model have already been set up, init runs after all columns have been set up.

    <body>Routine should be delegate execution to separate threads. This should be reworked to run the chain of Agents for each talk in a separate thread, not interfering with the main Routine in error cases.
